l it at handover.',\n      procurement: 'These add ons are low cost, stable supply items, so pushing them carries no sourcing risk.',\n      qa: 'Upselling sides keeps the core plate spec unchanged, so guest quality and consistency hold.' },\n    waste: {\n      finance: 'At $120 a week the run rate is about $6,200 a year here. Product not bought is product not written off, so it lifts margin and working capital.',\n      ops: 'The pattern is over prep on quiet weekdays. Tie prep par to the daily forecast so quieter days prep less.',\n      sales: 'Quiet weekdays drive both the waste and soft sales. Pair tighter prep with a small midweek feature to lift covers.',\n      procurement: 'Trim the next produce order about 10%. Right sizing the order is what closes the loop on the waste.',\n      qa: 'Most of this is over prep, not spoilage, so rotation is sound. Keep prep close to service to protect freshness.' },\n    foodcost: {\n      finance: 'The $1,240 weekly gap is about $64k a year here. It is operational variance against recipe, so it is high quality, in week recoverable margin.',\n      ops: 'The leak concentrates on the pizza station and Tuesday prep. A portion alert and a scoop fix the largest piece, then roll the control out.',\n      sales: 'Every $640 the floor adds in upsells is undone by $1,240 of over portioning. Brief both ends together so the win sticks.',\n      procurement: 'Part of the gap is input price, not just portioning. Lock mozzarella pricing with a reliable vendor to stop price creep widening it.',\n      qa: 'Over portioning is a spec breach as much as a cost one. Re train the line on the 4.0 oz standard to hold both consistency and margin.' },\n    supplier: {\n      finance: 'Chasing a $23 saving risks $3,100 of gross profit. On a deadline order, reliability is the cheaper choice.',\n      ops: 'Each vendor is scored on price, lead time and fill rate. Confirm the one that is both cheap enough and reliable enough to land in time.',\n     