n' } },\n    },\n    labor: {\n      outlet: { headline: 'Friday is one short and Saturday two short against forecast sales. Sunday is one over.',\n        sections: [\n          { h: 'What is happening', p: 'Forecast covers put Friday one person short and Saturday two short, with Sunday one over. Your busiest 90 minutes is Friday evening, which is exactly where the gap sits.' },\n          { h: 'How it is modelled', p: 'Cover is built from forecast covers per day part, not a flat headcount, so it tracks the busy windows. Balancing the week holds labour near 27% of sales.' },\n        ],\n        rec: { text: 'Add one Friday and two Saturday, move one from Sunday. Labour holds near 27% of sales.', money: 'protects ~$1,900 of sales' } },\n      cfo: { headline: 'Right sizing the week protects about $1,900 of sales and avoids unplanned overtime.',\n        sections: [\n          { h: 'The financial read', p: 'Understaffing the busy nights risks about $1,900 of sales walked, while the Sunday overstaffing is pure cost. Rebalancing holds labour near 27% of sales and removes the overtime risk on Saturday.' },\n          { h: 'Why it matters at scale', p: 'A point of unnecessary labour at a $20k a week outlet is over $10k a year. Across the estate, disciplined cover against forecast is one of the largest margin levers.' },\n        ],\n        rec: { text: 'Approve the rebalanced week and track labour as a percentage of sales against target.', money: 'holds labour at 27%' } },\n      coo: { headline: 'Coverage is mismatched to demand by day part. The fix is matching, not adding heads.',\n        sections: [\n          { h: 'The process read', p: 'The total hours are close to right, but they sit on the wrong days. Moving cover from Sunday to Friday and Saturday matches labour to demand without increasing the wage bill.' },\n          { h: 'What to standardise', p: 'Build every schedule from the demand forecast rather than copying last week. That is what stops the mismatch recurring across outlets.' },\n        ],\n        rec: { text: 'Build the schedule from the forecast and reallocate Sunday cover to the Friday peak.', money: 'no extra cost' } },\n      sales: { headline: 'Your busiest 90 minutes is understaffed. That is slow service on your best night.',\n        sections: [\n          { h: 'Why it matters', p: 'Friday 7 to 8:30pm is your peak and it is short. Slow service there means walked covers and a weaker upsell, exactly when tickets are most valuable.' },\n          { h: 'What to line up', p: 'With the Friday gap covered, the team can keep pace and still push the side of chips on the busiest tickets.' },\n        ],\n        rec: { text: 'Cover the Friday peak, then brief the team to keep attach high through the rush.', money: 'protects ~$1,900' } },\n    },\n    supplier: {\n      outlet: { headline: 'Order from Northside at $4.10 a lb. It is the cheapest source that still lands in time.',\n        sections: [\n          { h: 'What is happening', p: 'Three vendors can supply the mozzarella. Northside at $4.10 a lb lands Thursday, ahead of the deadline. Valley is cheaper at $3.85 but lands Friday and would miss the promotion.' },\n          { h: 'The tradeoff', p: 'Valley would save about $23 on the order but its fill rate has slipped to 91%, so on a promotion the stockout risk is not worth the saving.' },\n        ],\n        rec: { text: 'Place the 90 lb order with Northside to land Thursday, ahead of the weekend.', money: 'protects $3,100 GP' } },\n      cfo: { headline: 'Chasing a $23 saving risks $3,100 of gross profit. Reliability wins this one.',\n        sections: [\n          { h: 'The financial read', p: 'The cheaper vendor saves about $23 on this order but carries a 9% miss rate and a late delivery. Set against $3,100 of weekend gross profit at stake, the expected cost of the cheaper option is far higher.' },\n          { h: 'Supplier discipline', p: 'Fill rate and on time delivery belong in the sourcing decision,